issues.title: Feature Request: API for Converting SVG to PNG
issues.body:
Hello,

Firstly, I want to express my appreciation for this project. The speed and superb results have greatly benefitted my work. However, I've hit a snag and would appreciate your help.

I am currently working on a Python project where I need to incorporate the functionality that your project offers - specifically, converting SVG files to PNG. As you may know, Python isn't compatible with TypeScript, which leaves me in a difficult spot.

To navigate around this issue, I was hoping you might consider developing an API that takes an SVG file path URL and returns a PNG file path URL. This way, I can continue to benefit from your great work without the language barrier.

Given an SVG file path URL such as https://sample.com/inputfile.svg, the API would return the PNG file path URL, e.g., https://vincerubinetti.github.io/svg-to-png/output.png.

Looking forward to your constructive response.

Thank you.

issues.title: Firefox not rendering some svgs
issues.body:
Posting this here as an issue, rather than in the readme, because I think Firefox usage is relatively low.

There is a peculiar and frustrating bug in Firefox where it won't draw an SVG to a canvas if the root `<svg>` element doesn't have both `width` and `height` attributes explicitly specified, and in absolute units.

Stack Overflow post with top answer by the person who wrote most of the Firefox SVG code:
https://stackoverflow.com/questions/28690643/firefox-error-rendering-an-svg-image-to-html5-canvas-with-drawimage

Bug report:
https://bugzilla.mozilla.org/show_bug.cgi?id=700533

There is a workaround I can do, but it's a very dirty hack. It also could alter the behavior on other (more used) browsers, so I'd have to attempt to detect when it's firefox, which is brittle.

So, I'm going to leave it as is.

**If you're a user running into this issue**, try using another browser or add `width="xxx" height="xxx"` to your `<svg>`.

issues.title: Use entrez for journal lookup
issues.body:
Scimago rankings list journals by their full names, but iCite returns journals by their abbreviated/short/id names.

Previously I was using Scimago's search, which [doesn't reliably return the right journal as the first result](https://www.scimagojr.com/journalsearch.php?q=Commun+Biol). #16 changes this to scrape the [NLM catalog search](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nlmcatalog/?term=Commun+Biol[TA]) instead, which works fine, but it'd be more appropriate to use an actual API since once exists.

I can do [this query](https://eutils.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/eutils/esearch.fcgi?db=pubmed&term=Commun%20Biol[TA]&retmode=json) ([with TA](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/75512796/how-do-i-get-issns-and-full-journal-names-from-a-list-of-abbreviated-journal-nam)) to get a journal's (pubmed?) id, then [this query](https://eutils.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/eutils/esummary.fcgi?db=pubmed&id=39069530&retmode=json) to get its `fulljournalname`, which should hopefully be the same as the NLM catalog search shows (which so far seems to match what Scimago has as the title).

Scimago rankings aren't a high priority, but I'm guessing we'll eventually need to use the entrez tools to look something up, so I might as well create some type definitions and api funcs for them.

pullRequests.title: Initial pipeline implementation
pullRequests.body:
This is meant to be a basic vertical slice of the tech stack. Goals: flexible scraping, modular organization, type-safe from end to end, flexible data querying.

Right now the size of the data is very small and having an actual db might is probably overkill. I suppose it's good in that, if we're requested to get new data, anyone familiar with SQL could do it very quickly. It also may benefit us if the data grows to be an order of magnitude larger at some point, for more performant querying and even perhaps having a continuously running server that can get things dynamically (e.g. a more interactive dashboard). But if neither of these things happen, we may want to downgrade to just a simple `.json` file later.

See the related issues that this closes. This does not ingest e.g. Scimago citation information, but it does ingest iCite as a proof of concept. The actual contents of the webpage/report it generates is likely not useful (and doesn't explore the full depth of data ingested and integrated into the database), but again is just there as a proof of concept. In the next PR, I will focus on making an actual useful report. Casey suggested starting with per-core-project reports and a cfde-global report that list associated publications in order of date (and I guess some other high level info).

For now, the app is being deployed via Netlify (production version will be https://cfde-eval.netlify.app/ after this PR is merged).

High level description of changes, roughly in order of diff:

- github actions "compile" workflow to manually run this pipeline
- readmes in each sub folders as appropriate
- /app
  - vue app for creating the dashboard and pdf. vite, vue 3, composition api, typescript, eslint, prettier
  - pie chart component with apache echarts
- /data 
  - collection of node scripts run via tsx
  - type definitions for third party apis generated automatically
  - top-level "compile" script that runs high-level steps
  - sqlite database run by `better-sqlite3` library and interacted with via Kysely for type safety and query-constructing ergonomics
  - individual db tables for funding opportunities, projects/grants, and publications. to start, i just kept fields from third party apis that i thought were useful. schemas defined via ts.
  - report function that queries db to collate high-level data for webapp to display. exports it to json, runs webapp, and prints to pdf report. pdf report then deployed with webapp for public access.
  - funding opportunities scraped from cfde website html/pdf documents using playwright
  - projects/grant records obtained from reporter api
  - associated publications obtained from reported api, and supplemented with extra citation data from icite
  - more ingest sources to come later
  - bunch of useful util functions
    - pretty logging (will be important for debugging when the pipeline has more and more complex steps)
    - custom memoize func to avoid hitting apis too much (and possibly be rate limited)

commit.message:
Initial pipeline implementation (#6)

This is meant to be a basic vertical slice of the tech stack. Goals:
flexible scraping, modular organization, type-safe from end to end,
flexible data querying.

Right now the size of the data is very small and having an actual db
might is probably overkill. I suppose it's good in that, if we're
requested to get new data, anyone familiar with SQL could do it very
quickly. It also may benefit us if the data grows to be an order of
magnitude larger at some point, for more performant querying and even
perhaps having a continuously running server that can get things
dynamically (e.g. a more interactive dashboard). But if neither of these
things happen, we may want to downgrade to just a simple `.json` file
later.

See the related issues that this closes. This does not ingest e.g.
Scimago citation information, but it does ingest iCite as a proof of
concept. The actual contents of the webpage/report it generates is
likely not useful (and doesn't explore the full depth of data ingested
and integrated into the database), but again is just there as a proof of
concept. In the next PR, I will focus on making an actual useful report.
Casey suggested starting with per-core-project reports and a cfde-global
report that list associated publications in order of date (and I guess
some other high level info).

For now, the app is being deployed via Netlify (production version will
be https://cfde-eval.netlify.app/ after this PR is merged).

High level description of changes, roughly in order of diff:

- github actions "compile" workflow to manually run this pipeline
- readmes in each sub folders as appropriate
- /app
- vue app for creating the dashboard and pdf. vite, vue 3, composition
api, typescript, eslint, prettier
  - pie chart component with apache echarts
- /data 
  - collection of node scripts run via tsx
  - type definitions for third party apis generated automatically
  - top-level "compile" script that runs high-level steps
- sqlite database run by `better-sqlite3` library and interacted with
via Kysely for type safety and query-constructing ergonomics
- individual db tables for funding opportunities, projects/grants, and
publications. to start, i just kept fields from third party apis that i
thought were useful. schemas defined via ts.
- report function that queries db to collate high-level data for webapp
to display. exports it to json, runs webapp, and prints to pdf report.
pdf report then deployed with webapp for public access.
- funding opportunities scraped from cfde website html/pdf documents
using playwright
  - projects/grant records obtained from reporter api
- associated publications obtained from reported api, and supplemented
with extra citation data from icite
  - more ingest sources to come later
  - bunch of useful util functions
- pretty logging (will be important for debugging when the pipeline has
more and more complex steps)
- custom memoize func to avoid hitting apis too much (and possibly be
rate limited)
